Exploratory Data Analysis with Seaborn (Movies Dataset)¶

This notebook contains exploratory data analysis and visualizations using Seaborn for the movies dataset provided by vega datasets. The movies set contains nearlty 3200 movies and information about their budgets, profits, release dates, genres, and ratings. There is a significant amount of missing information in this dataset, so only rows with compete data once unused columns are removed will be considered.

The analysis below was used to make sense of the data set and provide a visually dynammic exploration of the data.

Correlation¶

To see how the quantitative variables are correlated with each other, we can use a correlation plot, which displays a matrix containing the correlation among all the variables. This is important for future modeling, since it is helpful to know that input variables are correlated with the response and whether there is cross correlation among the inputs.

In [183]:
corr = movies.corr().stack().reset_index(name = "correlation")

corr_plot = sns.relplot(data = corr, x = "level_0", y = "level_1", hue = "correlation", size = "correlation",
    palette="YlOrBr", aspect = 2.5, hue_norm = (-1, 1))

Pairplot¶

For a complete view of the relationship among qualitative variables and their distributions, we can create a pairplot, which visualizes the correlations in the form of a scatter plot. In the second pair plot, the scatter plots below the diagonal are displayed as density plots.

Qualitative Variables¶

The sections below attempt to make sense of the quantitative variables in this data set. In the first plot below containing the Pair Grid, we have grouped the movies by distribution company and sorted them by US Gross Profit. The plots to the right show how the remaining quantitative variables relate to distribtution companies sorted by profit. The plot shows that the most prolific distributors make movies with the highest budgets that make the most money. However, that doesn't always translate to the best movies, as Rotten Tomato Ratings and IMDB ratings are distributed more evenly across production companies.

The second plot shows how movie genre relates to the log transform of US Gross Profit. The graph shows that Action movies are the highest grossing genre, while Documentary is the lowest grossing.

Plot Three shows the distribution of US Gross Profit grouped by release month. The plot shows that the summer months and holiday season have a wider range of profit values with high grossing films.

The fourth plot compares the production budget and rotten tomatoes ranking to gross profit of movies labeled by genre. Budget and profit have a strong positive relationship, and action and western movies tend to have higher budgets and make more money. Rating and profit don't have as strong of a relationship, and Action and Western films, despite making more money, are not consistently rated better than films from other genres.
